00:14:31,292 --> 00:14:33,173
So if we start with product.

250
00:14:35,448 --> 00:14:40,830
One of the things which is kind of obvious, but really is probably worth restating, is

251
00:14:40,850 --> 00:14:42,270
the importance of control accuracy.

252
00:14:43,170 --> 00:14:46,811
We did an awful lot of work trying to figure out how to bring competitive gameplay to mobile.

253
00:14:47,351 --> 00:14:51,833
One of our hypotheses early on was, hey, we need to bring more natural controls, maybe

254
00:14:51,913 --> 00:14:55,133
gestures, swipes, gyroscope, any of those things into the game.

255
00:14:56,097 --> 00:14:58,038
Turns out players hate that across the board.

256
00:14:58,078 --> 00:15:00,059
We hated it ourselves, and we could validate it outside.

257
00:15:00,119 --> 00:15:04,140
Because one of the philosophies that has really paid off for us

258
00:15:04,220 --> 00:15:06,101
is to think through the control scheme of the game

259
00:15:06,161 --> 00:15:08,302
in such a way that you can ultimately,

260
00:15:08,362 --> 00:15:09,602
after about a minute or two of playing,

261
00:15:09,622 --> 00:15:11,103
you even forget that you're playing on a device.

262
00:15:11,543 --> 00:15:13,024
Your fingers just move naturally,

263
00:15:13,044 --> 00:15:15,485
and the only control input we accept is a tap.

264
00:15:16,325 --> 00:15:18,606
In fact, we spent a lot of time optimizing that tap

265
00:15:18,626 --> 00:15:22,848
to make sure that there is absolutely zero control latency across the board.

266
00:15:23,288 --> 00:15:25,008
And what's interesting is that we thought that

267
00:15:25,905 --> 00:15:29,827
In fact, leading to the next point, we thought that screen size would be an issue because

268
00:15:29,847 --> 00:15:33,228
you know what, fat fingers and a small touch screen, and you know what, even your fingers

269
00:15:33,248 --> 00:15:34,989
kind of obscure part of the touch screen.

270
00:15:35,950 --> 00:15:40,012
As it turns out, and we thought even originally we were a tablet gaming company because we

271
00:15:40,032 --> 00:15:44,174
figured how on earth could you last hit on a small five-inch screen.

272
00:15:44,734 --> 00:15:48,356
As it turns out, kids today are pretty incredible with their fingers and touch screens.

273
00:15:49,296 --> 00:15:52,438
In fact, we spent a long time figuring out controls that doesn't obscure the screen.

274
00:15:52,848 --> 00:15:57,171
But it turned out that actually a single tap-based control is like the equivalent of a, if you

275
00:15:57,191 --> 00:15:59,493
like, a mouse cursor and a keyboard in some ways.

276
00:15:59,513 --> 00:16:02,635
You have a mouse cursor that you're pressing with, and it turns out that your finger is

277
00:16:02,975 --> 00:16:04,236
actually just as accurate.

278
00:16:04,956 --> 00:16:08,679
And even if you feel like it's not quite as accurate, it turns out that when you need

279
00:16:08,719 --> 00:16:12,922
to do, execute moves like kiting or juking in a MOBA, which is basically say running

280
00:16:12,962 --> 00:16:15,064
in one direction and shooting in the other, running in the other direction, shooting in

281
00:16:15,084 --> 00:16:18,446
the other, that is a pretty complicated mechanical thing to do on a mouse.

282
00:16:18,466 --> 00:16:19,147
I mean, I've

283
00:16:19,967 --> 00:16:23,249
I'm a fairly sort of, I've played an awful lot of League of Legends and other, other

284
00:16:23,289 --> 00:16:24,750
styles of, other MOBAs on PC.

285
00:16:25,210 --> 00:16:28,892
And it is actually one of the hardest things I find, say if you play in a ranged carry

286
00:16:29,612 --> 00:16:34,595
and you need to move away while constantly shooting the opponent, or hitting the opponent,

287
00:16:34,615 --> 00:16:35,716
or basically attacking the opponent.

288
00:16:36,396 --> 00:16:40,579
That sort of thing is actually super easy to execute with your fingers and you can even

289
00:16:40,619 --> 00:16:42,860
create much more complicated maneuvers where you...

290
00:16:43,327 --> 00:16:47,749
So it's a preselected target, fire an ability, move, basic attack, and so on, with really

291
00:16:47,829 --> 00:16:48,810
natural taps.

292
00:16:49,490 --> 00:16:53,232
And one of the things that we've been delighted by is to see how many hyper-competitive players

293
00:16:53,472 --> 00:16:54,512
play on very small screens.

294
00:16:55,453 --> 00:17:00,215
In fact, the number two team in North America right now plays almost exclusively on five

295
00:17:00,235 --> 00:17:04,557
and a half inch screens on their iPhones, which is just incredible to me.

296
00:17:04,637 --> 00:17:09,539
Like I have a, for me, an iPhone 6 Plus is probably a good size screen to play on.

297
00:17:09,759 --> 00:17:13,160
Some people just play on iPads because they think they feel a need for the bigger screen.

298
00:17:13,959 --> 00:17:19,263
It turns out that what you lose in screen size, you actually gain in how quickly you

299
00:17:19,303 --> 00:17:19,623
can move.

300
00:17:19,723 --> 00:17:22,165
So it's a bit like the acceleration setting for your mouse.

301
00:17:22,285 --> 00:17:24,767
It's like, it's either less accurate or it's faster.

302
00:17:26,008 --> 00:17:27,349
More accurate or faster, that way.

303
00:17:27,950 --> 00:17:31,292
So it turns out that when you think about screen size, remember that the vast majority

304
00:17:31,332 --> 00:17:34,054
of the world is going to probably play on fairly small screens and it's worth thinking

305
00:17:34,094 --> 00:17:38,178
about making those guys first class consumers of your interface, whatever it is.

306
00:17:40,858 --> 00:17:41,778
Third is session length.

307
00:17:42,038 --> 00:17:44,179
So when we got started and we initially launched the game,

308
00:17:44,940 --> 00:17:46,961
Vainglory's average game length is about 20 minutes.

309
00:17:47,281 --> 00:17:49,122
An awful lot of people were pooh-poohing us, saying, look,

310
00:17:49,162 --> 00:17:49,823
it's a mobile game.

311
00:17:50,763 --> 00:17:52,965
It's been proven over and over again, mobile players don't

312
00:17:52,985 --> 00:17:54,645
play for longer than three minutes, because that's the

313
00:17:54,866 --> 00:17:56,647
sort of attention span of a mobile gamer.

314
00:17:57,667 --> 00:17:59,748
That may very well be true for a lot of mobile gamers.

315
00:18:00,149 --> 00:18:01,870
Turns out it really isn't true for everybody.

316
00:18:02,450 --> 00:18:04,491
20 minute session is perfectly fine for people who are

317
00:18:04,531 --> 00:18:05,552
interested in competitive gaming.

318
00:18:06,452 --> 00:18:08,073
Could we also make shorter game modes?

319
00:18:08,293 --> 00:18:08,453
Sure.

320
00:18:08,925 --> 00:18:13,469
But what we tried to do was create a session length which allows for tactical and strategic

321
00:18:13,609 --> 00:18:19,515
depth, which is akin to some of the best competitive games on PCs, which means that there are different

322
00:18:19,576 --> 00:18:20,376
phases to the game.

323
00:18:20,396 --> 00:18:22,438
There are phases where you outthink the opponent.

324
00:18:22,659 --> 00:18:25,902
You're basically playing a game of chess as well as an action game, if you like.

325
00:18:26,883 --> 00:18:27,984
You build, you counter build.

326
00:18:28,331 --> 00:18:31,012
You think about objectives, you think about rotations, you think about where you should

327
00:18:31,052 --> 00:18:32,733
be, about taking objectives at different times.

328
00:18:33,114 --> 00:18:38,276
And what we tried to do was squeeze that experience to as short as it can be while still maintaining

329
00:18:38,336 --> 00:18:41,538
the buildup, the tension, if you like, that something is building up, building up, building

330
00:18:41,578 --> 00:18:44,820
up and resolving itself in a team fight and an objective and the next thing.

331
00:18:45,580 --> 00:18:47,982
And then again, releasing that tension and then building up the tension again.

332
00:18:48,662 --> 00:18:52,064
And it turns out that that's worked really well for us.

333
00:18:52,664 --> 00:18:55,866
Our philosophy from the start was we didn't try to create a game.

334
00:18:56,802 --> 00:19:00,144
There was particularly easy to learn or a game that was particularly sort of

335
00:19:01,124 --> 00:19:04,005
on-boarding friendly or rewards you for absolutely everything

336
00:19:04,826 --> 00:19:08,327
with massive coin fountains and things which is what mid-core games are very good at today.

337
00:19:08,948 --> 00:19:12,009
We try to first and foremost solve for core gamers

338
00:19:12,309 --> 00:19:14,230
and try to figure out can we create a game that has

339
00:19:14,690 --> 00:19:16,991
legitimacy that we ourselves would love to play every day.

340
00:19:17,771 --> 00:19:21,173
In fact as a company we still play every day at 5 p.m. We have a company guild

341
00:19:21,633 --> 00:19:24,814
all of us play and even when we go home I still spend more of my time playing

342
00:19:24,875 --> 00:19:26,535
Jimmy and Glory today than any other game out there.

343
00:19:26,832 --> 00:19:31,434
Partially because I'm part of the community, but partially also because just as a core gamer, I'm hooked.

344
00:19:31,474 --> 00:19:33,175
I don't have as much time for PC gaming today.

345
00:19:33,575 --> 00:19:36,156
And I can sneak in a game of Vainglory almost anywhere right now,

346
00:19:36,256 --> 00:19:39,057
as opposed to having to be in front of my game PC at home.

347
00:19:40,197 --> 00:19:44,979
So, turns out, absolutely core gamers, like as was our philosophy from the start,

348
00:19:45,339 --> 00:19:48,180
we figure we're going to design for gamers regardless of platform,

349
00:19:48,200 --> 00:19:50,561
as opposed to designing for mobiles when it comes to session length.

350
00:19:51,321 --> 00:19:53,902
And that's paid off pretty well for us in terms of the growth of the competitive scene.

351
00:19:54,282 --> 00:19:55,863
It's probably also inhibited us from...

352
00:19:56,296 --> 00:20:01,401
shooting to the top of the charts immediately also because it obviously has to some degree

