00:25:15,014 --> 00:25:16,975
for us and something that we try and support as much as we can.

461
00:25:18,316 --> 00:25:19,337
And then finally, private beta.

462
00:25:19,787 --> 00:25:25,269
So this is something where for us, there's just a combinatorial complexity of trying

463
00:25:25,309 --> 00:25:29,771
to balance a game like Vainglory is too high for us to be able to do it internally.

464
00:25:30,812 --> 00:25:36,094
And by having a fairly large group of private beta players who get the new patch a couple

465
00:25:36,114 --> 00:25:40,056
of weeks before it's out, so we can try to figure out, find any problems with it, is

466
00:25:40,076 --> 00:25:40,636
very useful.

467
00:25:41,357 --> 00:25:45,018
But it's not just useful for that, it's actually a useful way of deepening our relationship

468
00:25:45,059 --> 00:25:48,740
with the top players in the world in such a way that we begin to understand sort of

469
00:25:48,760 --> 00:25:48,840
the...

470
00:25:49,230 --> 00:25:52,932
thoughts and hopes and fears of some of these players and begin to understand like what

471
00:25:53,152 --> 00:26:00,696
it is ultimately about the balancing of the in-game systems that make them come back every

472
00:26:00,716 --> 00:26:04,217
day and that make them feel very interested in helping push the competitive game moving

473
00:26:04,257 --> 00:26:04,497
forward.

474
00:26:05,518 --> 00:26:12,041
So, community has been, right from the start, something that's been incredibly deeply important

475
00:26:12,101 --> 00:26:12,301
to us.

476
00:26:12,341 --> 00:26:15,902
It's been something that we've really focused on from the start and something that we've

477
00:26:15,963 --> 00:26:18,003
found to be incredibly important across the board.

478
00:26:19,498 --> 00:26:23,520
However, marketing as a whole has been something that we've

479
00:26:23,560 --> 00:26:27,702
been learning, perhaps, more about than anything else.

480
00:26:27,942 --> 00:26:30,684
The first point here shouldn't come as a surprise to anyone.

481
00:26:30,724 --> 00:26:32,544
Players are pretty darn cynical out there.

482
00:26:33,145 --> 00:26:36,006
And if this comes as a surprise, I'm glad you're at

483
00:26:36,026 --> 00:26:37,567
GDC and you're learning about gaming.

484
00:26:37,587 --> 00:26:39,588
Because this thing has been true for a while.

485
00:26:39,628 --> 00:26:42,790
But what's interesting about this is, in particular, like a

486
00:26:42,830 --> 00:26:44,811
year ago when we came out and we said, hey, we're trying to

487
00:26:44,831 --> 00:26:46,432
make a competitive game on touchscreens.

488
00:26:47,024 --> 00:26:51,705
Like the vitriol that we would hear on places like Twitch and Reddit and other places where

489
00:26:51,725 --> 00:26:56,106
you would get unfiltered feedback, if you like, was one of massive skepticism and cynicism.

490
00:26:56,846 --> 00:27:00,507
And frankly, in some ways, we deserved it because as an industry, mobile gaming, we've

491
00:27:00,547 --> 00:27:02,207
been pretty bad at keeping our promises.

492
00:27:02,287 --> 00:27:08,448
We put out massive, beautiful 3D rendered screenshots and then coupled that with a game

493
00:27:08,788 --> 00:27:12,849
session experience which is very janky and two minutes and wants your money on day two

494
00:27:12,889 --> 00:27:14,349
and if you don't have any money, we don't care about you.

495
00:27:14,814 --> 00:27:18,597
kind of mobile gaming has been pretty bad at sort of creating that expectation.

496
00:27:18,637 --> 00:27:21,880
So when somebody stands up and says, hey, we want to make a PC style competitive

497
00:27:21,920 --> 00:27:24,222
experience like the ones that we grew up with on touchscreens.

498
00:27:24,562 --> 00:27:26,504
The first expectation is that, that we're lying.

499
00:27:27,005 --> 00:27:30,528
And that's actually been really an interesting kind of journey for us.

500
00:27:31,448 --> 00:27:34,051
Because all we've done is we've tried to combat that with

501
00:27:34,091 --> 00:27:35,152
authenticity across the board.

502
00:27:35,272 --> 00:27:38,394
And again, rather than trying to buy TV ads saying, hey, this is the thing you

503
00:27:38,414 --> 00:27:40,336
should play because it's awesome, we've just worked through the community.

504
00:27:41,097 --> 00:27:41,677
In fact, our best.

505
00:27:42,158 --> 00:27:44,418
community are best marketing assets across the board.

506
00:27:44,599 --> 00:27:48,000
The things that are brought people into the game are all community created across the board.

507
00:27:48,460 --> 00:27:51,761
And in fact, fundamentally when it comes to marketing a core game,

508
00:27:51,781 --> 00:27:55,042
and I believe this is actually true for most core games even on PC today,

509
00:27:56,202 --> 00:28:00,023
that by far the strongest marketing channel and the strongest way to drive awareness

510
00:28:00,143 --> 00:28:02,124
of the game is the player community itself.

511
00:28:02,544 --> 00:28:07,925
And in fact, our philosophy is very much one of we try to create awesome for our player base

512
00:28:08,325 --> 00:28:09,906
and if we make awesome for them.

513
00:28:10,434 --> 00:28:12,556
They hopefully will share it and if they do share it,

514
00:28:12,896 --> 00:28:15,379
we help with the spotlight on the things that they share.

515
00:28:15,399 --> 00:28:16,680
Because ultimately,

516
00:28:17,020 --> 00:28:19,002
Vainglory is not, the Vainglory experience is much,

517
00:28:19,843 --> 00:28:21,805
as much as we work on it every day and try to make it better,

518
00:28:22,265 --> 00:28:24,748
ultimately it's the players that create the experience for each other.

519
00:28:25,489 --> 00:28:27,170
And helping highlight that has been a big deal for us.

520
00:28:27,811 --> 00:28:29,172
So that's why all of these things

521
00:28:29,532 --> 00:28:33,196
have been, has been far more important for us than any form of ad spend or marketing,

522
00:28:33,837 --> 00:28:35,838
sort of internal marketing asset development.

523
00:28:37,106 --> 00:28:40,707
One of the things that we still struggle with a lot is how to message core game on touch

524
00:28:41,247 --> 00:28:44,888
because it's been messaged in so many ways and caused so much disappointment to date

525
00:28:45,488 --> 00:28:49,289
that in some ways we've actually decided to let the community speak for us on this and

526
00:28:49,309 --> 00:28:51,950
we simply amplify whatever it is that they feel is true about the product.

527
00:28:53,570 --> 00:28:54,530
So that's some marketing learnings.

528
00:28:55,330 --> 00:28:56,291
A couple of business learnings.

529
00:28:58,651 --> 00:28:59,831
Free to play versus pay to win.

530
00:29:01,219 --> 00:29:07,820
Right now, the touchscreen gaming, mobile gaming industry as business models are 95% plus pay to win.

531
00:29:08,061 --> 00:29:10,521
In some way or form, you are actually short-cutting.

532
00:29:10,541 --> 00:29:15,203
You become stronger than your neighbor, enemy, clanmate, whatever it might be by spending a bit of money.

533
00:29:16,243 --> 00:29:18,483
For a competitive game, that cannot be the case, right?

534
00:29:18,563 --> 00:29:23,345
We are always, have always been fundamentally focused on ensuring total fairness.

535
00:29:23,565 --> 00:29:26,726
When you come into the game, you're exactly as powerful as somebody who's been in the game for 10,000 hours.

536
00:29:27,829 --> 00:29:31,071
That creates a thing where you have to be much more careful

537
00:29:31,091 --> 00:29:33,012
about how you think about business models and how you

538
00:29:33,032 --> 00:29:35,493
think about what kind of in-game transactional models

539
00:29:35,513 --> 00:29:38,595
you create to ensure that the business model is orthogonal

540
00:29:38,875 --> 00:29:40,095
to your power in the game.

541
00:29:40,536 --> 00:29:42,317
That is a promise to our players, and it's a promise

542
00:29:42,357 --> 00:29:46,439
that we have kept and we aim to keep always moving forward.

543
00:29:46,859 --> 00:29:49,100
So it just requires you to rethink the systems.

544
00:29:49,120 --> 00:29:51,101
You can't simply just take systems from games that you've

545
00:29:51,121 --> 00:29:52,362
seen in mobile previously.

546
00:29:53,482 --> 00:29:54,683
And it's something, frankly, an area of

547
00:29:54,703 --> 00:29:56,104
learning for us as well.

548
00:29:57,840 --> 00:30:00,582
The other thing that should be obvious at this moment in time,

549
00:30:00,602 --> 00:30:02,844
but e-sports shouldn't really be thought of as a profit center

550
00:30:02,864 --> 00:30:03,644
at this moment in time.

551
00:30:04,725 --> 00:30:06,326
Yes, you have sponsors that get involved.

552
00:30:06,346 --> 00:30:07,827
Yes, tournament organizers get involved.

553
00:30:07,867 --> 00:30:10,448
Loads of, you can get revenue through all sorts

554
00:30:10,489 --> 00:30:11,169
of different sources.

555
00:30:11,989 --> 00:30:13,751
But I wouldn't think of it as a profit center.

556
00:30:13,991 --> 00:30:15,132
A lot of people say it's marketing,

557
00:30:15,172 --> 00:30:16,933
but I actually don't think it's marketing either.

558
00:30:17,153 --> 00:30:19,414
Because if people don't care about playing your game,

559
00:30:19,434 --> 00:30:21,456
they're not going to care about watching your game, typically.

560
00:30:21,796 --> 00:30:24,177
There are some edge cases, like when TSM joined Vainglory,

561
00:30:24,197 --> 00:30:26,179
a lot of TSM fans would check out, hey,

562
00:30:26,219 --> 00:30:27,740
what's this new game that TSM is playing?

563
00:30:28,047 --> 00:30:30,748
But the vast majority of cases, people watch the game

564
00:30:30,788 --> 00:30:31,468
that they love playing.

565
00:30:31,849 --> 00:30:35,130
So eSports, really, for us, is all about the product

566
00:30:35,171 --> 00:30:35,611
experience.

567
00:30:35,711 --> 00:30:38,532
It is fundamentally providing our players with the experience

568
00:30:38,592 --> 00:30:41,414
of being able to play the game at any time, watch the game

569
00:30:41,454 --> 00:30:44,155
being played at the highest level, learn from that

570
00:30:44,316 --> 00:30:49,979
gameplay, and get into the usage or consumption pattern

571
00:30:50,019 --> 00:30:52,620
that traditional sports has, where you play some, you watch

572
00:30:52,660 --> 00:30:54,021
some, you play some, you watch some.

573
00:30:54,381 --> 00:30:55,942
And that's simply what we want to provide through eSports.

574
00:30:58,512 --> 00:31:00,354
Finally, a couple of practical learnings before I wrap up.

575
00:31:01,815 --> 00:31:03,036
And these are kind of ridiculous, but

576
00:31:03,376 --> 00:31:05,218
it just has turned out to be things that we didn't expect.

577
00:31:06,258 --> 00:31:09,001
First thing, if you want to play in eSports one way or

578
00:31:09,041 --> 00:31:11,102
the other, you have to learn TV production.

579
00:31:11,242 --> 00:31:13,464
And that's like a brick and mortar business.

580
00:31:13,524 --> 00:31:14,825
It's literally event organization,

581
00:31:14,865 --> 00:31:19,009
thinking through everything from how do you run a live TV production that's

582
00:31:19,029 --> 00:31:22,692
gonna work out, everything from how to plan a run of show to think about talent,

583
00:31:22,712 --> 00:31:24,093
to training talent, to all of those things.

584
00:31:25,532 --> 00:31:26,553
It's pretty time intensive.

585
00:31:26,713 --> 00:31:29,874
If you're going to get into it, you need to appreciate that there's a lot to learn there.

586
00:31:30,194 --> 00:31:32,494
We've been doing this now for seven months and we're still learning tons.

587
00:31:33,275 --> 00:31:36,316
In fact, this stuff is so much fun that we sometimes worry that we put too much time

588
00:31:36,356 --> 00:31:38,916
into it because we ultimately need to build the game also.

589
00:31:39,457 --> 00:31:40,677
The other thing is learning Wi-Fi.

590
00:31:41,497 --> 00:31:46,319
It turns out Wi-Fi is actually black magic dark art in order to make Wi-Fi work really well,

591
00:31:46,619 --> 00:31:48,419
especially in crowded environments like this.

592
00:31:48,920 --> 00:31:51,781
It's something that, you know, when you have a tournament with an $80,000 prize pool,

593
00:31:53,733 --> 00:31:56,754
outcome cannot be determined by a ping spike because of your lazy Wi-Fi setup.

594
00:31:57,174 --> 00:32:00,235
So learning and understanding high-performance Wi-Fi is something you need to make a core

595
00:32:00,255 --> 00:32:01,036
competence to your company.

596
00:32:01,376 --> 00:32:01,896
It's ridiculous.

597
00:32:01,936 --> 00:32:03,776
I didn't expect to have to do it, but that is what it is.

598
00:32:04,077 --> 00:32:07,277
We originally dreamed that, hey, what if we just connect all the devices to, you know,

599
00:32:08,278 --> 00:32:09,398
to a hardwired cable.

600
00:32:09,758 --> 00:32:13,119
It turns out players want to play on their own device always, and they want to sit in

601
00:32:13,159 --> 00:32:16,280
all sorts of ridiculous positions while they're playing, and there's no way we can guarantee

602
00:32:16,300 --> 00:32:18,621
that fixed-line Internet will work into that specific device.

603
00:32:18,661 --> 00:32:20,902
So Wi-Fi is the way to go, and you need to learn about it.

604
00:32:22,766 --> 00:32:25,108
tournament setups in general, separate tournament servers,

605
00:32:25,148 --> 00:32:27,230
figuring out, do you need a separate tournament client,

606
00:32:27,450 --> 00:32:28,831
which I'm telling you already now,

607
00:32:28,871 --> 00:32:30,312
you will need a separate tournament client.

608
00:32:31,033 --> 00:32:32,194
Figuring out how you distribute those,

609
00:32:32,214 --> 00:32:32,955
how do you provision those,

610
00:32:32,975 --> 00:32:33,895
how do you make sure that everybody

611
00:32:33,915 --> 00:32:34,956
has all their heroes unlocked

612
00:32:35,016 --> 00:32:36,037
and all the other things

613
00:32:36,077 --> 00:32:37,418
that those tournament accounts need to have.

614
00:32:37,759 --> 00:32:39,000
How do you make sure that the integrity

615
00:32:39,020 --> 00:32:40,501
of the tournament environment is correct?

616
00:32:41,482 --> 00:32:43,023
All of that stuff is something that kind of,

617
00:32:43,664 --> 00:32:46,366
we've just had to learn and develop the specs for ourselves.

618
00:32:47,507 --> 00:32:49,108
But then finally, and perhaps more importantly,

619
00:32:49,609 --> 00:32:50,109
ultimately,

620
00:32:50,832 --> 00:32:54,814
When you think about eSports, it is fundamentally about the athletes.

621
00:32:55,515 --> 00:32:57,816
Just like the game is about the players in general,

622
00:32:58,756 --> 00:33:02,038
the biggest production doesn't matter if the athletes don't get to tell their story,

623
00:33:02,058 --> 00:33:03,439
don't get to have their moments of triumph.

624
00:33:03,959 --> 00:33:07,341
And this has been something that we've ended up learning a ton about.

625
00:33:08,162 --> 00:33:11,563
And to explain the kind of stories that end up being told behind the scenes,

626
00:33:11,583 --> 00:33:15,525
because at the end of the day, human stories is why players are interested in watching their game as an eSport.

627
00:33:15,926 --> 00:33:19,708
It is, yes, it is about watching the great plays and learning from them and the item builds and whatnot.

628
00:33:20,488 --> 00:33:23,749
But it really is about relating to that hero on screen.

629
00:33:24,770 --> 00:33:27,431
And last weekend we had this, we had, you know,

630
00:33:27,491 --> 00:33:30,192
TSM were the favorites, but they were nearly knocked out

631
00:33:31,152 --> 00:33:35,314
by a team with a 12-year-old ranged carry

632
00:33:35,534 --> 00:33:36,775
who has incredible mechanics.

633
00:33:36,795 --> 00:33:37,495
His name is D'Enzio.

634
00:33:38,359 --> 00:33:41,823
And he's probably one of the most talented players right now in North America.

635
00:33:42,584 --> 00:33:45,847
He's obviously still at school and he had his parents there, which is amazing.

636
00:33:45,867 --> 00:33:50,513
But I just want to play a quick video where Dienzio tells his story and tells the story

637
00:33:50,533 --> 00:33:55,459
of Halsey and Hammer's Velocity to give you a sense of just what kind of stories come

638
00:33:55,499 --> 00:33:55,739
out of this.

639
00:34:07,690 --> 00:34:12,153
I think my teammates are really, really good and passionate on how they play.

640
00:34:12,213 --> 00:34:14,975
Like, they really do like playing their roles.

641
00:34:15,135 --> 00:34:17,916
Like Aloha, he's really good at what he does.

642
00:34:17,996 --> 00:34:23,180
When he's playing a hero and he plays it good, he almost never messes up.

643
00:34:23,360 --> 00:34:25,361
And Alvainz, he's just such a great support.

644
00:34:25,721 --> 00:34:27,522
Like, if he's on Catherine, we would just win.

645
00:34:28,923 --> 00:34:30,705
DnZo has no limit.

646
00:34:31,045 --> 00:34:34,288
I've seen him grow into a player that's tilted after one death.

647
00:34:34,428 --> 00:34:38,371
Then we go in to play a top four team in Nemesis,

648
00:34:38,671 --> 00:34:41,373
and he goes 1-5 in the first couple minutes,

649
00:34:41,473 --> 00:34:43,075
then he goes and carries the rest of the game.

650
00:34:43,662 --> 00:34:47,484
In the first qualifier, we lost to Vega in the round of 16.

651
00:34:47,784 --> 00:34:50,406
That was our first qualifier together.

652
00:34:50,426 --> 00:34:55,349
And then we really wanted to go to the live championships.

653
00:34:55,389 --> 00:34:59,552
And we knew we had to pull off a winning streak in the qualifier, and that's what we did.

654
00:35:00,112 --> 00:35:01,653
In the second qualifier, we came...

655
00:35:02,802 --> 00:35:14,557
We were very close to beating TSM, and this was huge for us mentally because we're showing ourselves, not only everybody else, that we can compete at this level.

656
00:35:14,948 --> 00:35:21,212
When we tied the series with TSM, we kind of like didn't focus at that point.

657
00:35:21,292 --> 00:35:22,133
We thought it was over.

658
00:35:22,173 --> 00:35:23,734
There's no way we can mess up.

659
00:35:24,235 --> 00:35:25,736
And then we choked and messed it up.

660
00:35:26,416 --> 00:35:27,317
We had it.

661
00:35:27,617 --> 00:35:28,318
We had the game.

662
00:35:28,378 --> 00:35:29,258
It was ours.

663
00:35:29,639 --> 00:35:32,140
And then when we lost, I was so disappointed.

664
00:35:32,621 --> 00:35:33,842
They didn't deserve that win.

665
00:35:34,562 --> 00:35:35,463
I want my revenge.

666
00:35:35,823 --> 00:35:38,965
We're not going to make that mistake again and we're going to keep our minds focused

667
00:35:39,546 --> 00:35:43,208
for our matches and make sure we take it home and then celebrate.

668
00:35:46,028 --> 00:35:47,569
I'm going to say fear Dienzio.

669
00:35:47,789 --> 00:35:50,769
If you ever see him out in solo queue, surrender.

670
00:35:51,109 --> 00:35:53,170
There's not much you can do.

671
00:35:54,790 --> 00:35:56,951
So these type of human stories is ultimately

672
00:35:56,991 --> 00:35:58,231
what e-sports engenders.

673
00:35:58,291 --> 00:36:01,392
And that is for us ultimately the fundamental emotional

674
00:36:01,432 --> 00:36:03,812
resonance that we want to create when it comes to the game.

675
00:36:04,312 --> 00:36:07,433
And that's the thing that we hope that we can help surface

676
00:36:07,533 --> 00:36:08,613
across our community.

677
00:36:08,673 --> 00:36:10,233
And that's the meaning of e-sports for us.

678
00:36:11,514 --> 00:36:13,574
So before I leave you guys, just.

679
00:36:15,205 --> 00:36:17,286
Just a final reminder why we are doing this.

680
00:36:17,767 --> 00:36:19,547
We talk a lot about the meta of different games.

681
00:36:19,628 --> 00:36:21,889
Well, we feel like the meta of the industry fundamentally

682
00:36:22,749 --> 00:36:24,950
is that companies have built incredible businesses

683
00:36:25,530 --> 00:36:28,152
off the back of a PC install base of about 700 to 800

684
00:36:28,232 --> 00:36:30,113
million gaming PCs out there.

685
00:36:30,493 --> 00:36:33,774
Incredible happy communities of, well, sometimes salty,

686
00:36:33,794 --> 00:36:36,856
but mostly happy communities of core players

687
00:36:37,056 --> 00:36:40,518
off the back of fundamentally only less than a fifth

688
00:36:40,738 --> 00:36:43,219
of the world's population having access to these devices.

689
00:36:43,660 --> 00:36:46,001
And that base isn't really growing that much, that fast.

690
00:36:46,322 --> 00:36:48,123
By the end of this year, there will be over 3 billion

691
00:36:48,143 --> 00:36:50,465
touchscreen devices that can play a game like Vainglory.

692
00:36:51,586 --> 00:36:53,107
We're still very early in this cycle.

693
00:36:53,247 --> 00:36:55,088
We believe over the next three to five to seven years,

694
00:36:55,168 --> 00:36:57,310
somebody's going to go out there and build a company

695
00:36:57,330 --> 00:37:00,672
that is three to five to seven times as large.

696
00:37:00,692 --> 00:37:02,553
